  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The first, temporal, is when the meaning of a word or a term drifts over time.",
    "This might be because of shifts in community usage, like one materials scientist pointed out, \"in like 2008-ish, the Chinese community decided that the word shock [testing] also means high rate Kolsky bar testing\" (5).",
    "It could also be because the referents of the words themselves have changed, as in the case of committee organization in a local government: \"if you're looking for committee reports from before 2018 and you're looking for hospitals, the committee on hospitals didn't exist until 2018.\" (40).",
    "The second, domain-specific change, is when different fields use different words or terms for very similar things: \"I call it a surrogate model.",
    "If you ask a statistician what they're going to call it, they're going to call it an emulator."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
